title: Grateful Dead Live at Shoreline Amphitheatre on 1989-06-21
description: Hideaway, Touch Of Gray, Minglewood Blues, Ramble On Rose, Box Of Rain, Dire Wolf, When I Paint My Masterpiece, Row Jimmy, Cassidy, Deal Scarlet Begonias-> Hell In A Bucket*, Ship of Fools*, Estimated Prophet*-> Eyes Of The World*-> Drums-> Jam-> Truckin'*-> The Other One*-> Morning Dew*-> Turn On Your Love Light*, E: Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: shoreline what a venue huh to have been built on an old landfill..truly though this show isnt so bad kind of a cloudy sound but nice and jammed 3.8 stars

pay per view special this was a killer show. I've got the video and must have watched it 100 times in the last 16 years    HOLY SHIT !!!  16 years ago  dam i better get this on a dvd before it gets to ragged to watch .  check out the break between sets. all the heads in action. its a MUST have for any video/dvd/film collector of the dead. Yo hairbag!

Was this the Pay Per View? Nice show as I recall..I had the whole thing on tape (including the lead up to the show)..I don't know what happened to it..they were plagued with equip problems to start and then the PPV ended before the show did :-(

A great venue though..saw a few shows there..used to live in Mt View but left before they built Shoreline..I used to frequent the driving range that was once there!

Jim

Classic Dead Reaction... What do you do when you've sold tens of thousands of tickets and hundreds of thousands of subscriptions for a pay-per-view event?  If you're the Dead, you have tons of equipment troubles and have a really haggard beginning ;-)

Man, this is why we all love these guys so much!  Instead of folding however, once Bobby gets over the static coming out of his amp, the show starts to cook... (near Minglewood).  

The sound is real good, and Jerry's voice is solid.  Brent, Phil and the Rhythm Devils play fantastic.  Bobby struggles at first, but comes around.  You can tell that Jerry is giggling to himself about the whole thing, and really tries to make a good showing of the night.

Good fun.  Shoreline in Summer.  Late 80's.  You get the picture.  Download later parts of 1st set and 2nd.

summer solstice 1989 Not my last show, but my last trip. A gift from a beautiful couple on the lawn.
The show had some oddities, bad sound to start, and I could've done without Clarence Clemons for example, but the highs were incredibly HIGH. Hideway was a cool little gift. It is the second set that really shines. The drums is epic and the Turckin>Other One. I was dancing like a loon at the top of the theatre to that.
One of my least favorite shows I ever saw. Second set in particular was real shabby.
